From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v94 — PHY-derived netif_carrier (workaround MAC bit 0)

v93 boot result: probe + netdev register succeed cleanly, mts0 → enp0s20f1.
Host RTL8153 partner reports `Link detected: yes, Speed: 1000Mb/s,
Duplex: Full` — link is electrically working at 1Gbps.  PS4 PHY reports
healthy (BMSR=0x7969 AN done, reg5=0xcde1 partner ACK + 100/10
advertise, reg10=0x3800 both receivers OK).

BUT BAR+0x04 bit 0 (MAC's internal link-detect bit) never latches in
v93 — pattern 0x00040084 (TX_DONE + LINK_CHANGE + bit18) never appears
in the IRQ histogram, only 0x00040000 (bit18) fires repeatedly.  So
the ISR's `if (status & MTS_IRQ_LINK_CHANGE)` never executes, never
calls netif_carrier_on, and Linux drops every TX packet with
"NO-CARRIER" (proven: TX_dropped counter went 23→32 on a 3-packet
ping, TX_packets stayed 0).

Why bit 0 latched in v91 but not v93:  v91's RX descriptor ring was
zero-filled (all-zero descriptors).  HW was probably erroring on every
RX fetch, and that error path generated the link-change IRQ as a side
effect.  v93's RX ring is *correctly* pre-filled with valid skb DMA
addresses, so HW processes the ring cleanly and never trips the
side-effect link-change IRQ.

Fix: trust the PHY directly.  In the existing phy_ctrl kthread (3s
heartbeat), evaluate BMSR bit 5 (AN done) AND reg 5 bit 14 (partner
ACK).  When both true, call netif_carrier_on().  This bypasses the
MAC's broken bit-0 latch.

The ISR path still calls netif_carrier_on/off on link-change IRQ if
the MAC ever does latch bit 0 — both paths are idempotent so they
compose cleanly.

Cost: 3s latency on initial carrier-up (kthread period).  Acceptable.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -198,6 +198,7 @@
 	u8 phy_addr;
 	bool link_logged_once;
 	bool last_phy_link_up;
+	bool last_phy_carrier;	/* v94: PHY-derived netif_carrier state */
 	bool initial_an_done;
 	unsigned int link_down_iterations;
 
@@ -1151,6 +1152,47 @@
 			mts->link_down_iterations++;
 		}
 
+		/*
+		 * v94: PHY-derived carrier detection.  v93 boot proved the MAC's
+		 * BAR+0x04 bit 0 doesn't always latch even when the PHY-level
+		 * link is fully healthy (AN done, both receivers OK, partner
+		 * ACK).  When that bit fails to latch the link-change IRQ never
+		 * fires, the ISR never calls netif_carrier_on, and Linux refuses
+		 * to call ndo_start_xmit -> all packets get dropped at the qdisc
+		 * layer.
+		 *
+		 * Workaround: trust the PHY directly.  If BMSR bit 5 (AN done)
+		 * AND reg 5 bit 14 (partner ACK) are both set, the partner has
+		 * acknowledged us at the AN layer and the link is functionally
+		 * up — even if the MAC's status bit hasn't latched.  Toggle
+		 * netif_carrier from this thread so userspace can use the
+		 * interface.  Re-checked every 3s with the existing heartbeat.
+		 */
+		{
+			u16 v_bmsr = 0xffff, v_lpa = 0xffff;
+			bool phy_carrier;
+
+			if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x01, &v_bmsr) == 0 &&
+			    mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x05, &v_lpa) == 0) {
+				phy_carrier = (v_bmsr & 0x0020) &&
+					      (v_lpa & 0x4000);
+				if (mts->ndev && phy_carrier != mts->last_phy_carrier) {
+					if (phy_carrier) {
+						netif_carrier_on(mts->ndev);
+						dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+							 "v94: netif_carrier_on (PHY-level: BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
+							 v_bmsr, v_lpa);
+					} else {
+						netif_carrier_off(mts->ndev);
+						dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+							 "v94: netif_carrier_off (BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
+							 v_bmsr, v_lpa);
+					}
+					mts->last_phy_carrier = phy_carrier;
+				}
+			}
+		}
+
 		msleep_interruptible(MTS_PHY_CTRL_PERIOD_MS);
 	}
 	return 0;
